1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,320
We've already been working with strings a great deal in this course.

2

00:00:03,320  -->  00:00:06,240
Let's review them in a bit more detail.

3

00:00:06,240  -->  00:00:10,600
Let's imagine you're a storyteller crafting a very exciting story.

4

00:00:10,600  -->  00:00:12,180
In your exciting story,

5

00:00:12,180  -->  00:00:17,420
every word sentence and paragraph is represented as a sequence of characters.

6

00:00:17,420  -->  00:00:20,920
In Python, these sequences are known as strings.

7

00:00:20,920  -->  00:00:23,680
Whether you're working with text in a story,

8

00:00:23,680  -->  00:00:25,220
a list of commands,

9

00:00:25,220  -->  00:00:27,080
or even just a user name,

10

00:00:27,080  -->  00:00:31,865
strings are essential for storing and manipulating text data of characters.

11

00:00:31,865  -->  00:00:35,970
You'll notice something is a string because it will have quotes around it,

12

00:00:35,970  -->  00:00:39,450
like you see here, much different than a number,

13

00:00:39,450  -->  00:00:41,110
which has no quotations.

14

00:00:41,110  -->  00:00:44,930
You can create a string using either single or double quotes,

15

00:00:44,930  -->  00:00:48,370
both will do in the world of strings in Python.

16

00:00:48,370  -->  00:00:50,210
Think of this like writing a note.

17

00:00:50,210  -->  00:00:52,750
Whether you use single or double quotations,

18

00:00:52,750  -->  00:00:54,150
doesn't matter very much,

19

00:00:54,150  -->  00:00:55,915
as long as you're consistent.

20

00:00:55,915  -->  00:00:57,770
When you're working on a tech team,

21

00:00:57,770  -->  00:01:01,420
your team will probably adopt a specific style.

22

00:01:01,420  -->  00:01:06,310
Make sure to subscribe to those types of standards for consistency.
